    <h2>Conquer Tai Shan Mountain</h2>
    <p>Mount Tai (Chinese: 泰山; pinyin: Tai Shān) is a mountain of historical and cultural significance located north of Tai'an city, Shandong, China. Its highest point is called Jade Emperor Peak (simplified Chinese: 玉皇顶; traditional Chinese: 玉皇頂; pinyin: Yùhuáng Dǐng) at 1,545 meters (5,069 ft) but according to agency reports under the Chinese Government is 1,532.7 meters (5,029 ft). <br>
    Thai Son is known as Dong Nhac, one of the Five Famous Mountains in China and is considered the most important mountain among them. In addition, Taishan is also a place with a worship history of at least 3,000 years, and has been one of China's most important religious ritual centers throughout history.</p>
<h3 class="mountaintitle">Location</h3>
    <p>Taishan is located in western Shandong province, just north of the city of Tai'an and south of the province's capital city of Jinan. Its elevation ranges from 150 to 1,545 meters (492 to 5,069 ft) above sea level and covers an area of ​​426 square kilometers (164 sq mi). Its highest point is called "Jade Emperor Peak", 1545 meters high.</p>
<img class="img6" src="{{asset('blog/files/nuithaison.jpg')}}" alt="núi thái sơn">

<h3 class="mountaintitle">Cultural significance</h3>
    <p>Mount Tai has importance in Chinese religion. According to historical records, Taishan became a sacred place visited by emperors for offerings and meditation since the Zhou Dynasty before 1,000 BC. A total of 72 emperors were recorded to have visited here. Writers have also come here to get inspired, compose poetry, write essays, draw and take photos. Therefore, many cultural relics were left behind in the mountains. <br>

    The journey at Thai Son is about 7,200 steps with 6,293 main steps leading to the top of the mountain, through 11 gates, 14 arches, 14 shops and 4 gazebos. A total of 22 temples, 97 ruins, 819 stone slabs and 1,018 stone walls and cliffs at Thai Son.</p>
<h4 class="mountaintitlee">big temple</h4>
    <p>Dai Mieu (Chinese: 岱庙; pinyin: Dàimiào) is the largest and most complete ancient building complex located at the foot of Mount Tai. The temple was built during the Qin Dynasty and since the Han Dynasty, its design has been a replica of the imperial palace making it one of only three extant structures in China with the characteristics of a palace. The royal palace along with the Forbidden City and the Temple of Confucius in Khuc Phu. Dai Mieu has 5 large halls and many small buildings. Its center is the Heavenly Palace built in 1008 during the reign of Song Huy Tong. There is also a mural dating from 1009 that is 62 meters long and 3.3 meters high. The great temple is surrounded by cypress trees from the Han Dynasty that are 2,100 years old. In addition, many stone stele from the Song Huy Tong period are preserved here, some of which were mounted on Quy Phu and later also in the Qianlong period.</p>
<h4 class="mountaintitlee">Bixia Temple</h4>
    <p>The Bich Ha Temple (Chinese: 碧霞祠; pinyin: Bìxiá Cí) located near the top of the mountain is a large complex building combining many types of construction materials from metal, wood, brick, and stone structures. It was built to worship the goddess Bich Ha. From Thai Son Temple to Bich Ha there are many stone slabs and inscriptions and ancient houses along the way, and from the foot of the mountain to the top are 6,660 stone steps winding along the mountain slopes.</p>
<h4 class="mountaintitlee">Other projects</h4>
    <p>Some other works include Jade Emperor Temple (玉皇庙), Qing Emperor Palace (青帝宫), Confucius Temple (孔子庙), Dau Mau Palace (斗母宫), Pho Chieu Pagoda (普照寺). Many visitors also came to enjoy the scenery and left many writings here. Typically, Confucius said: "Dang Thai Son is the youngest child in the world" or Du Phu: "The supreme leader, the most powerful group of small mountains". Thai Son is also famous for its inscriptions, including the words "Ngu Nhac monoton" (五岳独尊) or "Nhat quan feng" (日观峰). It was inscribed by a member of Ai Tan Giac La in 1907 and appeared on the reverse side of the 5-currency note in the 5th series. <br>

    Some other prominent examples include Xa Than cliff (舍身崖), Ai Than cliff (爱身崖), Nhat Quan peak (日观峰), Nguyet Quan peak, Chiem Lo Dai (瞻鲁台), Tham Hai peak jelly (探海石)</p>


